From 74db3b58e7209ab70d50fb570b342ccb4419e390 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Keno Fischer <keno@juliahub.com>
Date: Fri, 17 Jul 2026 15:42:21 +0000
Subject: [PATCH 1/8] futex: Replay the wakeup consumed by a robust waiter
 killed before acquiring

A robust futex unlock stores 0 over the whole futex value - wiping
FUTEX_WAITERS - and wakes a single waiter. That wakeup is a one-shot
notification: the protocol relies on its recipient to either acquire
the futex (and eventually unlock while aware of the remaining
contention) or re-arm FUTEX_WAITERS before sleeping again.

If the woken waiter is killed before it can do either, and a third
task re-acquired the futex through the uncontended fast path in the
meantime, the notification is lost: the exit time robust list walk
finds the waiter's armed list_op_pending, reads a futex value owned by
a live task and - correctly - leaves the futex value alone, but it
also discards the wakeup. The new owner sees no FUTEX_WAITERS when it
unlocks and wakes nobody. The remaining waiters sleep forever behind a
free futex:

  A owns the futex, B and C sleep in FUTEX_WAIT
                                        uval == A | FUTEX_WAITERS
  A robust unlock: store 0, FUTEX_WAKE(1) wakes B
                                        uval == 0
  D fast path acquire: cmpxchg(0 -> D)
                                        uval == D, no FUTEX_WAITERS
  B killed before acting on the wakeup
  B exit walk, pending op: owner D != B -> no action
  D unlock: no FUTEX_WAITERS -> no wake
                                        C sleeps forever

Commit ca16d5bee598 ("futex: Prevent robust futex exit race") handles
the adjacent case where the futex value is still 0 when the walk runs,
by waking a potential waiter. Extend that handling to the owner
mismatch case: when a pending non PI lock operation of the dying task
is discarded because the futex is owned by someone else, wake one
waiter. The futex value is not touched - the owner is alive - and a
spurious wakeup is harmless: woken waiters re-evaluate the futex value
and re-arm FUTEX_WAITERS before sleeping again, which also repairs the
wiped bit for the remaining sleepers.

The window was found by model checking the robust futex wait/wake
interactions with TLC. A deterministic selftest is added in the
following patch.

This patch was developed with the assistance of Claude (an AI
assistant by Anthropic); the author reviewed, validated and takes
responsibility for the changes.

Fixes: 0771dfefc9e5 ("[PATCH] lightweight robust futexes: core")
Signed-off-by: Keno Fischer <keno@juliahub.com>
---
 kernel/futex/core.c | 19 ++++++++++++++++++-
 1 file changed, 18 insertions(+), 1 deletion(-)

diff --git a/kernel/futex/core.c b/kernel/futex/core.c
index 179b26e9c934..9944112d55fd 100644
--- a/kernel/futex/core.c
+++ b/kernel/futex/core.c
@@ -1025,8 +1025,25 @@ static int handle_futex_death(u32 __user *uaddr, struct task_struct *curr,
 		return 0;
 	}
 
-	if (owner != task_pid_vnr(curr))
+	if (owner != task_pid_vnr(curr)) {
+		/*
+		 * The dying task's pending op may have consumed the wake up
+		 * notification of a robust unlock: woken, then killed before
+		 * it could act on it. The robust unlock wiped the whole
+		 * futex value including FUTEX_WAITERS, so the owner which
+		 * re-acquired the lock afterwards will unlock through the
+		 * uncontended fast path and never wake the remaining
+		 * waiters. Nothing may be modified here - the lock has a
+		 * live owner - but a potential waiter must be woken to keep
+		 * the wake up chain alive. The woken waiter re-evaluates
+		 * the futex value and re-arms FUTEX_WAITERS before waiting
+		 * again, so a spurious wake up is harmless.
+		 */
+		if (pending_op && !pi)
+			futex_wake(uaddr, FLAGS_SIZE_32 | FLAGS_SHARED, NULL, 1,
+				   FUTEX_BITSET_MATCH_ANY);
 		return 0;
+	}
 
 	/*
 	 * Ok, this dying thread is truly holding a futex
